				 Pension managers to start work in June
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 In safe hands																								New Delhi, Nov. 27: The three entities chosen to manage the governments new pension scheme will start operating from June next year.																								According to the pension regulator, the State Bank of India (SBI), the Life Insurance Corporation of India (LIC) and UTI Asset Management Company will form separate companies to manage the pensions of about 3 lakh government employees who entered the service after January 2004.																								D. Swarup, chairman of the Pension Fund Regulatory and Development Authority, said the SBI would manage 55 per cent of the corpus.																								UTI Asset will manage 40 per cent of the corpus and the LIC, 5 per cent.																								Employees will have to pick from two options. One option is 100 per cent investment in bonds; the other is 5 per cent investment in stocks, 10 per cent in equity oriented mutual fund schemes and 85 per cent in bonds.																								National Securities Depository Limited (NSDL) is the central record keeping agency for the scheme.																								NSDL has been appointed for 10 years and will set up call centres to provide information to account holders, according to C.B. Bhave, the chairman and managing director of NSDL.																								Swarup said the government would bear all the expenses of account holders vis--vis NSDL. 																								These are an annual fee of Rs 350, a one-time charge of Rs 50 and a payment of Rs 10 per transaction.																								NSDL will issue a permanent retirement account number, on the lines of a PAN card, and provide annual statements. 																								The size of the corpus is now Rs 2,000 crore, with central government employees contributing Rs 1,200 crore and state government staff, Rs 800 crore.																								Nineteen states have agreed to follow the new pension scheme. 																								Kerala, Bengal and Tripura have refused to join the scheme. 
